{
  "doc_id": "49840",
  "text": "Several studies reported higher CSF a-syn concentrations in patients with AD versus both individuals suffering from other NDs and HCs. However, these results are conflicting, probably due to substantial intersite methodological differences [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . These include different pre-intra-analytical procedures and assays, performed for CSF a-syn assessment, and different recruitment criteria. Previous studies exploring CSF a-syn concentrations in AD were performed in dementia patients or subjects with prodromal (mild cognitive impairment) forms of the disease [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] .",
